  "prompt": "How do you find out the full number of Pi?",
  "response": "Pi (\u03c0) is an irrational number, which means that its decimal representation goes on infinitely without repeating. Therefore, it is impossible to determine the \"full number\" of pi because it has infinitely many digits. \n\nHowever, pi is often approximated to a certain number of decimal places for practical purposes. Common approximations include:\n- 3.14 (as used in most elementary calculations)\n- 22/7 (a familiar fractional approximation)\n- 3.141592653589793 (to 15 decimal places)\n\nFor higher precision calculations, you can find pi to millions or even billions of digits using computational methods. As of now, pi has been calculated to more than 31 trillion decimal places using powerful computers.\n\nIf you need more digits of pi for calculations, you can use a tool like `math.pi` in Python's standard library for a fairly precise value, or refer to online resources that generate pi to a large number of decimal places.\n\nWould you like more information on how to compute or retrieve a specific number of decimal places of pi?",
